Two Pointer Approach
The two-pointer approach is an efficient algorithm technique using two indices to traverse linear data structures (arrays/linked lists) to solve problems,
often reducing time complexity from \(O(n^2)\) to \(O(n)\). It is primarily used on sorted data to find pairs, manage sub-arrays, or reverse elements,
with pointers moving in the same or opposite directions.

Core Types of Two-Pointer Approaches
Opposite Ends (Converging): 
One pointer starts at the beginning left = 0, and the other at the end right = n-1. They move toward each other until they meet.
    Common Use: Sorted array pair sum, palindrome verification, reversing arrays.

Same Direction (Fast/Slow or Sliding Window): 
Both pointers start at the beginning but move at different speeds or conditions.
    Fast/Slow: Used to find the middle element or detect cycles in linked lists.
    Sliding Window: One pointer expands the window, while the other contracts it.

Parallel Pointers:
Used on two separate arrays/lists, moving through them simultaneously.
    Common Use: Merging two sorted arrays
